And they used the internet. One of the children earned a full ride college scholarship based on his SAT/ACT scores. He is now a successful undertaker. The daughter is a happy mother. My mother -- the professional educator -- was amazed that a rank amateur could get such a good result. &#10;In the 19th century in the United States, there were few &quot;public&quot; schools anywhere. But late in the century, 2/3 of the population was literate. Parents taught their kids to read at home. And they were pretty good at it. &#10;We also need to get over the idea that if a child is not in Head Start or some kind of pre-school that they are doomed. We need an education system that responds to individual's needs regardless of age or their inability to fit into the government prescribed age determined straight jacket. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1107" language="en" documentId="61" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Fortunatia" date="7/30/2013 3:21 AM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375147318-746-304" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="61" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="593"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="594" end="815"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="816" end="1107"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>